  "body": "### Environment information\r\n\r\n* `brownie` Version: 1.16.0\r\n* `hardhat` Version: 2.6.0\r\n* Python Version: 3.9.6\r\n* OS: linux\r\n\r\n### What was wrong?\r\n\r\nExiting brownie console (using `quit()` or Ctrl-D) doesn't fully terminate hardhat network.\r\n\r\nSteps to reproduce:\r\n```\r\n# Launch new local hardhat RPC client\r\nbrownie console --network hardhat\r\n# Terminate brownie (should terminate hardhat as well)\r\nquit()\r\n\r\n# Launch new instance\r\nbrownie console --network hardhat\r\n# This reconnects to old instance implying hardhat wasn't terminated properly\r\n```\r\n\r\n### How can it be fixed?\r\n\r\nHardhat process tree spans multiple levels\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/27727946/129193497-5bf6579e-b0b9-45d8-826f-bc2f16f111d0.png)\r\n\r\nThis is the rpc process according to brownie\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/27727946/129194680-3a6c0d91-6500-4ff1-87fe-6cf2de1bf73c.png)\r\n\r\nBut the actual rpc is two levels below the primary process\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/27727946/129194384-d698eafd-5473-4489-b7ea-e7bd353bbaf1.png)\r\n\r\nWe should probably recursively kill all child processes here using `self.process.children(recursive=True)` instead of just killing the immediate children\r\nhttps://github.com/eth-brownie/brownie/blob/master/brownie/network/rpc/__init__.py#L141-L145\r\n",
